reviews.review_text: ummm... the tracks are all effed up recording sounds nice, but still... this need to be fixed

balance This is a very nice recording.  Not sure I'd normally give it 5 stars but I need to offset the one star review based on the track mis-ordering.  Sheesh, rating the quality of the track order instead of the show/recording is not the intent of the ratings.
Same here Five stars to get the average rating up for a historical show re Close Encounters. Nice effort on the matrix.
Soundboard? Sounds more like a mic under a pillow which is under the head of a sleeping taper.

blazing Ya know, Nick P., the same tapes which circulated at SPS circulated at PA as well ... I think you got to branch out a little, now that everything is available.

Nevertheless, this is good stuff.

Best EVER The 45 minutes or so from the end of Drums to the end of NFA are probably my favorite 45 continuous minute of Grateful Dead music ever.  The Other One, while not as lengthy as the early '70s versions, is simply otherworldy. The jam in St. Stephen is the peak of joyful Jerry energy. The NFAs from this era were generally great, and this one gets out there further than most.

Even the A&A, after a bit of a rough start, smokes pretty thoroughly. 

The rest of the show is very good, but it's this last segment that puts it among the greatest Dead shows ever.

Note: The tracks in this version are out of order and mislabeled.  Don't let that discourage you.
Excellent matrix of a hot show Yeah, the track order is messed up and mislabelled. This show smokes.  A 5 star performance and a 5 star matrix. If you do not give this a listen you are a fool.

A Legendary Second Set !!! I'm not sure what samstein66 and rox247 are smoking, but simply put, this is a smoking, legendary, MUST HAVE second set for every collection.  With five or six hundred shows, I haven't heard this one in quite some time.  And I almost forget (ah, not) how incredible a significant portion of the second is and how much I love it.  The first set is competent.  And Jer is still struggling with his early January laryngitis, so I can't give the show as a whole five stars.  But I'm not writing this review or rating it as a whole.

Having a cherished, so-so Maxell II AUD in my collection since the early eighties, I am still amazed at how much these matrix mixes improve the listenability.  With earphones on, I want to shed a tear at how beautiful, how clean, and how inspiring it is, humming to the Close Encounters Space into St.Stephen just before sunrise this morning.  My god, Box Burner is absolutely on the mark.  As a continuation of '77's magnificence, if you don't have this on your desktop and in your iPod or your iPhone, you're missing a pre and post Drumz hour of pure, unadulterated pleasure.

Thanks Chris for this wonderful addition to the Archive.
